    <h1>On so&#xAD;cial me&#xAD;dia</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201010/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-10-10"><time>2020-10-10</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE | TRENDING</span>
        - <span role="byline">PHOTOS: STE&#xAD;FANIE SUN/WEIBO</span>
    </section>

    <p>SPOT THE DIF­FER­ENCES: A ne­ti­zen in China claimed ear­lier this week to have seen Sin­ga­porean singer Ste­fanie Sun on a high-speed train in the coun­try.</p>
    <p>A photo of the al­leged sight­ing was posted on so­cial me­dia (above), in which a masked woman is pic­tured doz­ing off on the train.</p>
    <p>But the 42-year-old Man­dopop queen took to Weibo on Thurs­day to clar­ify in Chi­nese: “I re­ally didn’t take the high-speed rail.”</p>
    <p>Sun, who cel­e­brates two decades in show business this year, de­cided to recre­ate the scene.</p>
    <p>In a photo she posted on Weibo (top), she is wear­ing a black shirt and face mask, and looks to be doz­ing off as well. Like the first photo, there is a man with a back­pack and a woman us­ing a mo­bile phone.</p>
    <p>Last Thurs­day, Sun posted rare photos of her chil­dren to mark the Mid-Au­tumn Fes­ti­val. She has a son, who turns eight this month, and a daughter, two, with her Dutch-In­done­sian hus­band Nadim van der Ros.</p>

